SOFTWARE USED: Windows/Linux OS and Cisco Packet Tracer.

tHEORY:
A Ring topology is a modified version of bus topology where every node is connected in a 
closed-loop forming peer-to-peer LAN topology. 
Every node in a ring topology has precisely two connections. The Adjacent node pairs are 
connected directly, whereas the non-adjacent nodes are indirectly connected via various nodes. 
Ring topology supports a unidirectional communication pattern where sending and receiving of 
data occurs via TOKEN. 

PROCEDURE: 
(COMMON FOR ALL TOPOLOGIES) 
Step 1: Create Network Topology 
● Drag and place devices: PCs, Switches, Hubs, Routers. 
● Arrange them according to the selected topology. 
● Connect devices using appropriate cables: 
o Straight-through → PC to Switch / Hub 
o Cross-over → PC to PC 
o Serial → Router to Router 
Step 2: Assign IP Addresses 
● Click on PC →Desktop →IP config→Assign IP address and click on Default mask. 
Step 3: Test Connectivity 
● Use Simple PDU tool to send packets. 
● Place the packet at sender and receiver PCs to check link is connected 
● Or open PC → Desktop → Command Prompt/ Terminal 
e.g give the command, ping 192.168.1.2 
Step 4: Switch to Simulation Mode 
● Use Simulation to see hop by hop delivery of such packet flow with Protocol used 
● Observe packet movement. 
● Note: 
o Time of packet travel (delay) 
o Hop count 
o Dropped packets 
o Delivery success/fail 
Step 5: Repeat for All Topologies 
RESULT:  Various network topologies (Bus, Star, Ring, Mesh, Hybrid) were successfully 
configured in Cisco Packet Tracer. Performance was compared using delay, hop count, packet 
loss, and throughput.
